BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260329T200000Z
DTEND:20260329T220000Z
LOCATION:Auer Hall &amp\; LIVE@jacobs
SUMMARY:Weiss Kaplan Stumpf Trio: Yael Weiss\, piano (guest)\; Mark Kapla
 n\, violin\; Peter Stumpf\, cello
DESCRIPTION:Enjoy this performance from almost anywhere in the world viaL
 IVE@jacobs!Repertoire  Beethoven: Piano Trio in E-Flat Major\, Op. 1 No. 
 1 (1795)L. Boulanger: Deux pi├©ces en trio (1917)R. Schumann: Piano Trio 
 No. 1 in D Minor\, Op. 63 (1847)About the Artists  Combining the talents 
 of three award-winning soloists\, the Weiss Kaplan Stumpf Trio (WKS Trio)
 brings to each performance its distinctive fusion of authority and experi
 ence\, energy\, and passion. The trio embraces the music of the future wh
 ile offering fresh insights into three centuries of masterworks. The WKS 
 Trio has earned widespread critical acclaim in performances throughout th
 e United States\, Europe\, Asia\, and the Middle East since its inception
  in 2001 with recital programs featured in such major venues as the Kenne
 dy Center and Wigmore Hall and festival engagements including Changwon an
 d Jeju Island in Korea and the Festival of the Sound in Canada. In fall 2
 023\, the trio released The Complete Beethoven Trios as a 3-CD set on Bri
 dge Records. The new album garnered outstanding critical response\, inclu
 ding reviews from the international Gramophone Magazine ("Absolute Magic"
 )\, World Music Report ("Like the legendary Beaux Arts Trio\, the Weiss K
 aplan Stumpf Trio's trademark is an uncommonly rich and full tone and the
  kind of rapt and attentive ensemble that only comes from magical empathy
  that they wear like a second skin from years of playing together")\, and
  Fanfare Magazine ("the best set since the classic set with the young Dan
 ial Barenboim\, Pinchas Zukerman\, and Jacqueline du Pr├®ŌĆöthe spirit of
  Beethoven's music comes through with profound understanding"). The WKS T
 rio's commitment to Beethoven has also included performances of his Tripl
 e Concerto in the United States and Europe\, including a Prague Festival 
 appearance praised for its "rare timbral refinement\, nobility and virtuo
 sic brilliance" (Lidove noviny\, Prague). The new Beethoven CD set takes 
 its place alongside their other recordings on Bridge Records\, featuring 
 discs with new American music as well as trios of Brahms and Smetana. The
  latter received the enthusiastic praise of Fanfare Magazine ("you cannot
  afford to be without this ŌĆ” [it] may just be the best of the best Brah
 ms B Major Trio recordings"). Devoted to new music\, the trio has commiss
 ioned ensemble and concerto works for trio from distinguished composers L
 era Auerbach\, Paul Chihara\, Michael Gilbertson\, Michael Hersch\, and P
 aul Lansky\, and have recorded many of these along with others by America
 n composers Fred Lerdahl\, Chen Yi\, Clancy Newman\, and Paul Schoenfeld.
   Laureate of the legendary Leventritt Competition\, violinist Mark Kapla
 n is a major soloist of international distinction\, having performed with
  nearly every American\, European\, and Australian orchestra. His extensi
 ve discography of over 45 commercial CDs includes concertos\, solo and ch
 amber works from Paganini\, Bart├│k\, Berg\, and Sarasate\, to Schubert\,
  Brahms\, and Schumann. To his credit are two complete recordings of Bach
 's solo violin works\, the more recent of these on Bridge. Since 2005\, h
 e has been violin professor at the Indiana University Jacobs School of Mu
 sic\, following a decade as professor at UCLA. Kaplan is a graduate of Th
 e Juilliard School\, where he studied with Dorothy DeLay.  Cellist Peter 
 Stumpf is known world-wide as a soloist\, chamber musician\, and orchestr
 al leader. As a soloist\, he has appeared with the Boston Symphony\, Los 
 Angeles Philharmonic\, and Philadelphia Orchestra. He has participated in
  music festivals at Bridgehampton\, Marlboro\, Ravinia\, and Santa Fe and
  has appeared on the chamber music series at Carnegie Hall\, AliceTully H
 all\, the Kennedy Center\, the Boston Celebrity Series\, the Cologne Phil
 armonie\, the Concertgebouw\, and Casals Hall in Tokyo. He was a founding
  member of the Johannes String Quartet\, and his awards include first pri
 ze in the Washington International Competition. He was principal cellist 
 of the Los Angeles Philharmonic after serving as associate principal cell
 ist of the Philadelphia Orchestra. He has served on the faculties of the 
 New England Conservatory\, the University of Southern California\, and is
  presently professor of cello at the Jacobs School.  Pianist Yael Weiss h
 as toured the United States\, Europe\, Japan\, and South America to great
  acclaim\, both in recital and as soloist with major orchestras. Winner o
 f the Naumburg and Kosciuszko Foundation Chopin competitions\, Weiss has 
 recorded solo works by over a dozen composers. She has served on the facu
 lties of the Jacobs School and University of California Santa Barbara and
  has given master classes worldwide. She is the curator and performer of 
 32 Bright Clouds: Beethoven Conversations Around the World\, a groundbrea
 king global commissioning project presenting piano music from countries o
 f conflict and unrest alongside Beethoven's 32 piano sonatas. An advocate
  for the power of music in the service of peace\, she is a frequent guest
  on national and international media. Weiss is a graduate of the Peabody 
 Conservatory and Mannes College\, where she studied with Leon Fleisher an
 d Richard Goode. Meeting URL: https://liveatjacobs.music.indiana.edu/
